Particles are 
also pictorially shown, with their vertical coordinate representing 
their energy.}
\label{fig:wells}
\end{figure}


In \Fig{fig:wells} we represent schematically the two model potentials at $z=0$, 
as a function of $x$ and $y$. In this pictorial representation, the vertical 
coordinate of the particles corresponds to their energy.

In both cases, we denote as $V_0$ the barrier height: 
it is $V_0=p_0^2/2m$ for the SDW, and $V_0=V({\bm{\mathrm{{0}}}})-V({\bm{\mathrm{{r}}}}_{min})$, 
the difference of potential energy between the barrier top and the well 
minima in the case of the HGDW.

The quantity we use to follow the macroscopic dynamics of the double-well 
problem is the fraction of particles in the left well at time $t$

